					<source>HDR video</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="118" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The High Dynamic Range (HDR) video feature applies HDR processing to the video stream of the capture device.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="119" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn926682)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>Determine if HDR video is supported by checking the <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">HdrVideoControl.Supported</pc></pc> property.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="120" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The HDR video control supports three modes: on, off, and automatic, which means that the device dynamically determines if HDR video processing would improve the media capture and, if so, enables HDR video.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="121" translate="yes">
				<originalData>
					<data id="id1">[</data>
					<data id="id2">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn926683)</data>
					<data id="id3">**</data>
					<data id="id4">**</data>
				</originalData>
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>To determine if a particular mode is supported on the current device, check to see if the <pc dataRefEnd="id2" dataRefStart="id1" id="p1"><pc dataRefEnd="id4" dataRefStart="id3" id="p2">HdrVideoControl.SupportedModes</pc></pc> collection contains the desired mode.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
